            <ObservedData>
              <Attribute Type="Description">In a 21-year-old man (P1), born of consanguineous Indian parents, with autoinflammation with episodic fever and immune dysregulation (AIFID; 620795), Oda et al. (2024) identified a homozygous 1-bp duplication (c.220dupC, NM_030974.4) in the SHARPIN gene, resulting in a frameshift and premature termination (Leu74ProfsTer86) in the coiled-coil domain. The mutation, which was found by trio-based exome sequencing, segregated with the disorder in the family. The mutation was not present in the homozygous state in gnomAD. Fibroblasts and peripheral blood mononuclear cells derived from the patient showed reduced, but not absent, SHARPIN mRNA, absence of a full-length or truncated SHARPIN protein, reduced HOIP expression, and decreased HOIL1 recruitment to the LUBAC complex. These defects could be restored with wildtype SHARPIN. After TNF stimulation, patient fibroblasts showed a slight reduction in linear ubiquitinated chains and a slight reduction in IKBA (164008) phosphorylation compared to controls, suggesting reduced activation of NFKB. Patient cells also showed increased sensitivity to TNF-induced apoptosis under certain conditions. The patient had onset of symptoms in early childhood and later responded well to treatment with TNF inhibitors.</Attribute>
